story: It’s hard when someone in your family is diagnosed with cancer, especially in the midst of a pandemic with there being so many limitations with isolation thrown in on top of it all, nothing ever prepares you for it being so close to home. The specialist Macmillan team are there to support patients and also their families. With them being such a help to families , I would like to raise some money to give back to and support them after being there for us , so they can continue their hard work during these unprecedented times! I will be running 5k per day for 10 days starting January 1st if anyone would like to donate it will be very much appreciated! Thank you ❤️ Mam you have made me the proudest daughter for showing how strong you really are , this is for you x

eventName: The Locked Inn Quiz - Christmas Special
story:
The world has gone to pot, so I'm putting on a Christmas special of The Locked Inn Quiz for my friends this Wednesday 23rd December at 8pm (8.15 start).

I know you've done loads of quizzes this year, but mine are ace and lots of fun, and let's face it what else are you going to do on Christmas Eve Eve when the country is shut. So get yourself a drink and let's make the best of a bad situation.

This time we're raising money for Macmillan Cancer Support. It's minimum £5 per adult or whatever you can afford as it's been a real tough year for some, but if you can give more that would be fantastic.

I will write a question specifically for the first 20 people who donate and I will try and include a question for everyone who donates before 5pm on Tuesday. It's going to be family friendly so there'll be something in there for all ages.

I'm keeping it to people I know for now but please register beforehand here - https://bit.ly/34vz6YW


Thanks... see you on Wednesday!

story:
As some of you will know my Father in Law lost his battle to cancer in November 2020. At the time we needed them most, Macmillan were there to support both my Father in Law and the family. We cannot thank them enough!

In addition to this, my Mum was also diagnosed, and fortunately, successfully treated for skin cancer in 2020.

With 1 in 2 people affected by cancer, it is very likely me or you will need support from organisations like Macmillan in the future.

Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. story:
I’m hoping to raise some funds for this incredible cause by completing forty days of fitness  Anybody who knows me, knows I only enjoy swimming and walking  I hate running and workouts - mainly because I can’t do them! So I’m pledging to workout and run two miles every day for forty days  (please bear with me on the running front, I’ll be terribly slow and rubbish, I literally can’t run a tap without collapsing)

It would be absolutely amazing if you could donate any spare change you have, and you’ll be safe in the knowledge that you’re giving money,  whilst I hate every single second of what I’m doing... you’d  literally be paying for me to suffer! 

I’ll be posting my routine plan and evidence of my exercise, and let’s be honest, we all need a good laugh right now! 

Thanks for supporting my fundraising. Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. Thanks for reading, and if you’ve donated, you’ve done an amazing thing! Thank you 💚

charity.name: St John Ambulance
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I’m a member of St John Ambulance and really enjoy the online meetings as Covid-19 hasn’t allowed me to attend a proper meeting yet. I’m also part way through my Silver Duke of Edinburgh Award and because of the pandemic I decided that raising money for St John  Ambulance would allow me to complete the community section.  I love running! So I thought I world run 100 miles and hopefully raise £100 for a really great charity.

I would be very grateful for any support. I know it’s not the easiest time to ask for donations but I please help if you can.

Thank you so much,

Charlotte 

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Many thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

On the 9th December, Maureen suddenly fell ill at home and only had a few desperate seconds of communication with me before she lost consciousness. She had suffered a failure in a major artery and was 
immediately admitted to East Surrey Hospital. Despite the best efforts of doctors and nursing staff,  there was nothing they could do and she sadly passed away on 11th December, aged 81.

Despite being a cancer and stroke survivor, and being bed- and wheelchair-bound following a fall and subsequent hip operation in1919, her mind and her spirit remained active and vibrant to the end. She will be sorely missed by myself, her dear children David & Carolyn and her grandchildren Johnny, Gurpreet and Emily.

We believe that charitable donations are a far more fitting tribute to Maureen rather than sending flowers. I believe she would think it appropriate if all contributions were to go to the British Heart Foundation, who will hopefully one day develop pioneering technology and equipment able to detect a whole host of heart and circulatory diseases in advance, and thereby extend the lives of others in future.

Without this life-threatening disease which took her from us so suddenly, Maureen could have been with us for several more years - long enough to see her grandchildren grow into adults and start their own families.

I welcome your contribution which you can make by donating through JustGiving. It is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they will never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

Dave & family
title: In Memory of Maureen - my lovely wife of 50 years

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
When I was just 12 years old I tragically lost my dad to a heart attack he suffered in the middle of the night. By doing this and raising money for this charity hopefully it will help young people come to terms with such a tragic loss. 

The older you get it doesn’t get any easier you just learn how to accept it, process it and be a support system to loved ones around you. 

This past year I also lost my uncle (on my dad’s side) to a heart attack so I will be doing the run in memory of the Osborne brothers and hopefully raising as much as I can for British Heart Foundation. ❤️

charity.name: Guide Dogs
charity.registrationNumber: in England and Wales 209617 and Scotland SC038979
story:
I am walking 100,000 steps in 50 days. I hope to raise money for Gude Dogs, a vital service for people such as me who need these super duper dogs for our independence and life back! 

However you take on your 100, get sponsored to do it and help us supporting people living with sight loss. You could complete 100 metres, 100 minutes, 100 days be creative!The sponsorship money you raise will make a difference. £100 could pay for five hours' training at a Guide Dogs training school.It's thanks to people like you that we can continue to provide life-changing services, like our guide dogs, to people with sight loss. So, a huge thank you and lots of luck for your challenge!#TeamGuideDogs

eventName: Premier Inn London Waterloo GOSH Appeal
story: Great Ormond Street Hospital supports seriously ill children from all over the UK. Every day 619 children and young people arrive at GOSH to receive care and life saving treatments to ensure they can continue to lead healthy lives. Since 2012, Premier Inn and Restaurants have been proud partners of Great Ormond Street Hospital Charity and we know our passionate teams have taken part in many brilliant fundraising events as well as volunteering at national events around the country and at the hospital. During these uncertain times our teams continue to achieve incredible things, challenging themselves to conquer their Everest and take care of their wellbeing. We are looking to continue the fantastic fundraising achieved through our partnership by supporting our teams in their creative and dedicated ways of personal achievement. We are #innthistogether and together, we can continue our incredible work.

story:
As a teacher, I have the pleasure of spending everyday with 30 beautiful children and the joy and laughter they spread is highly infections.



‘Children are not only innocent and curious but also optimistic and joyful and essentially happy. They are in short, everything adults wish they could be.’



This year has been a tough one on all of us, I couldn’t imagine also having the stress of having a child in GOSH too. Hearing all the stories of how happy and optimistic all the children who attend GOSH are, I knew I had to do something this year.



Therefore, I’m putting on my running gear, embracing the rain (and possibly snow) and running 31 miles throughout January. Every donation small or large will be greatly appreciated. Lets say thank you to everyone at GOSH and give those little angels who are staying happy and optimistic a little bit of help this year! Thank you!

Me and Alvin will be taking part in the 31 mile run to raise money for great orman Street. 

When our little girl Teigen was born the second day she was taken to GOSH where she spent 9 days there this was such a hard time for us as new parents, The surgeons,Doctors,nurses were absolutely amazing and we cant thank them enough for all there hard work and support, 

This is our way of saying thank you and hope we can help other children that are at GOSH 

GOSH is a absolute amazing hospital that needs all the donations to help.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

In 2015, when I was 20 weeks pregnant with my 3rd child, we found out that there was an issue with one of the baby's kidneys. At the time, we knew only that it was dilated, nothing else. 

Fast forward 20 weeks of questions, tests and huge anxiety on our part. Our daughter, Tess, was born with a complicated duplex kidney. Basically, the top part of Tess' right kidney was happily making urine but couldn't drain because it's ureter was blocked. Tess was in pain, she cried, constantly, no medicine helped her and we were struggling to cope with the lack of support we felt we had.

When Tess was 4 months old, we went to Great Ormond Street Hospital for Tess to undergo tests on her kidney. We then met Professor Cuckow. He explained to us that Tess needed to undergo surgery to remove her kidney. He made us feel instantly better - he told us that it was important it was done quickly but that she would recover and be well. 

Shortly after this meeting, Professor Cuckow and his team operated on Tess, they managed to save the bottom half of her kidney. One of his doctors told us in recovery, that Tess' kidney had swollen to the size of an orange, taking up a huge part of her abdomen and close to blocking her bladder completely.

We stayed for a week under Great Ormond Street's care. Every single person we met during that time had a huge impact on us, we will be forever grateful.

Tess is now almost 5. She no longer needs medication. The only lasting issue is her need to stay hydrated as she is prone to infection. We have one more check up with the team at Great Ormond Street before we are signed off - although we were reassured at our last appointment that, although we're signed off, they will always be there for Tess.

Tess is a healthy, happy and clever girl, we are so proud of her. She is also very proud of her 'rainbow scar' (her words!) as are we. 

Running 31 miles in January will be a fair challenge for me. I'll update my social media to keep track of how I'm getting on. Any pennies you can spare to support me...or, more importantly, Great Ormond Street, are much appreciated.

story:
COVID-19 has delayed the lifesaving surgery that our little boy needs but this spring we are hoping that Elliot’s heart operation will finally go ahead. All we want for Christmas is to know that he will be fine and that we will get to celebrate many more Christmases together but there is nothing that I can do to get that reassurance. What I can do is run and raise money for an amazing hospital that saves the lives of children all over the world! Please donate what you can if you can <3

story:
Thanks for taking the time to read and support me.

Me and my dad are doing the half marathon so 16 miles walking through the City of London to Raise money for GOSHH.  

We have taken many of walks as father and daughter but never this big or for charity. I wouldn’t want to be walking beside anyone else! I am hoping to raise £300 at least for the comfort or equipment for these families with sick children. Beyond my imagination being a mother myself I couldn’t even begin to imagine how these families cope with it. I want to make a difference and do my bit for this charity because I know how hard the staff work they even become family to these families! 

We can’t thank the NHS enough for everything they’ve done this year!.... so here goes let’s give something back!!!

story:
Hi everyone thanks for taking your time to look at my page or sponsor me! This means so much to me! This year has shown us all how special family is and for those families who have sick children some who may never get better. I wanted to raise money for Great Ormond Street because being a mum myself I couldn’t even begin to imagine what these warrior families have been through and In hope that my donation towards the charity can bring comfort or equipment to at least one family. So with your help please sponsor me and my dad walking the streets of London for 16miles across the Capital in the cold for such an amazing Charity. I will post updates abs videos of our journey for you to follow us! 

Many thanks from one warm heart to another xxx

story:
Im geeking out for GOSH and taking on a gaming challenge to raise money for the seriously ill children,  their families and the NHS staff at Great Ormond Street Hospital. 

As GOSH plays a role in the national response to the COVID-19 crisis by treating more children from hospitals across London, resources will become increasingly stretched.   

The hospital needs the support of Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity) now more than ever, so it can continue to deliver the best, life-saving care for seriously ill children. 

Your support will help keep me going when things get tough and give me the power-up I need to complete this challenge. Its quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the give now button on the right.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

Bobby T was a great friend and band-mate of ours who unfortunately succumbed to this horrible disease on 26 October 2020. Which was a terrible shock to us all - he seemed to be recovering so well about surgery and chemo. His corkscrew hair was even starting to grow back during the summer, albeit a bit straighter than before. 

And he never once complained or moaned about his predicament. In fact his reaction on hearing that he had 'only weeks' to live was "some people live a long time, some people don't". He died 4 days later. We think he'd just had enough....

Any donations to this highly-worthy cause would be very much appreciated. Together maybe we can one day rid the world of this terrible disease.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. story:
Gaming is something I don't find that much time for, but we should always find time for raising money for Cancer Research UK. The work they do is amazing and hopefully, one day, we will rid the world of the horribleness of going through it and seeing loved ones in a bad way.

story:
My Dad (Trev) is fighting cancer for the third time, this time Lung and Brain cancer. 

Having successfully beaten tongue and prostate cancer already he is now having radiotherapy 5 times a week and chemotherapy for 6 weeks. This time around he will most likely lose his hair.

I am shaving my own head in January to show my support for him, and if I can "raise a few quid" at the same time towards this cause that would be great!

Thanks for taking the time to read and hopefully donate!
Dan

We aim to hit £150 by Christmas Day, so please give as generously as you can and your donations are much appreciated!

We can’t use cash this year, or collect food/shopping to drop off at food banks - so we are going digital! All contributions need to be made online via this page 👍🏼 

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I used to run relatively regularly before my daughter was born but haven’t done any really since. I need this challenge to push myself and get back to it. It may not sound like much to some but this will be epic for me. I am so looking forward to doing this and hopefully raising money for such a worthwhile cause. 

Thank you for reading 😁

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit our JustGiving page.

The help, support and compassion the Marie Curie nurses provided during Thea's time at home allowed her to live out her final days in the company of her family and friends just as she wished. charity.description: RNLI volunteer lifeboat crews provide a 24-hour search and rescue service all around the UK and Ireland, while lifeguards keep a careful watch on the UK’s busiest beaches. RNLI lifesaving and drowning prevention depend on supporter fundraising and the generous donations that you and others give.
charity.name: RNLI - Royal National Lifeboat Institution
story:
Too many people are still drowning. More than ever we need the RNLI’s help. As a charity, the RNLI depends on our donations so it can go on saving lives and keeping us and our loved ones safe. 

RNLI lifesavers are our lifeline. They’re the lifeboat crews who provide 24-hour search and rescue right around the UK and Ireland. The lifeguards keeping watch on 240 of the busiest beaches in the UK and Channel Islands. And the RNLI safety teams and educators working tirelessly to stop people getting into trouble in the first place.

Thank you.

charity.name: WWF-UK
story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
story: Throughout the globe Covid-19 has spread rapidly. Although UK has seen its own share of illness and death we are very lucky enough to have first class healthcare service and government support in this crisis. Unfortunately others around the world are not so lucky. In an attempt to give back to those in need this February Isaac Guppy, Cam Graetz, Max Waldron and Julian Hannah have set themselves a challenge to run 300km each throughout the month (averaging 10km a day) in order to raise money for UNICEF. UNICEF, also known as the united nations children’s fund, is a United Nations agency responsible for providing humanitarian and developmental aid to children worldwide. We extend the invitation to anyone who would like to join us on our ‘Rona Run’ or set your own challenge for the month and help support those in need!

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: I am challenging myself to drink nothing but water this January. I am taking on the ultimate detox by avoiding caffeine, alcohol and all other drinks while supporting WaterAid. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across Ethiopia. Together, we will bring clean water to 50,000 people in Ethiopia and thousands more around the world, helping them change their own lives, forever. If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk
